  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "<b><size=120%>Basic Troubleshooting for Interns</size></b>\r\n\r\nListen,
    I\u2019m tired of fixing the same logic errors. If you're trying to get the secondary
    systems to acknowledge a state change, remember two things:\r\n\r\n<b>1. Define
    the Reality:</b>\r\nA status check (we call it a <color=#004080>bool</color>)
    is binary. It\u2019s either on or it isn\u2019t. If the flashlight is working,
    the state is <color=#004080>true</color>. If the bulb is burnt out, the state
    is <color=#004080>false</color>. It\u2019s not 'maybe.'\r\n\r\n<b>2. Don't leave
    the thought hanging:</b>\r\nThe compiler is a perfectionist. Every time you make
    a declaration\u2014like telling the system the light is now off\u2014you <color=#800000><b>must</b></color>
    terminate the line.\r\n\r\n<i>Example for the Flashlight:</i>\r\n<color=#006060>isFlashlightWorking</color>
    = <color=#004080>false</color><color=#A0522D><b>;</b></color>\r\n\r\nSee that
    little dot-and-tail at the end? That <color=#A0522D>semicolon</color> is the
    difference between a working door and a total system lockout. Don't forget it
    again, or I'm revoking your coffee machine privileges.\r\n\r\n\u2014 <i>Senior
    Tech Miller</i>"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
